// Aliased construction binds the SOURCE type, not a same-named export.
//
// `hew::aliassrc` exports two DISTINCT records: `Payload` (one `code` field)
// and `Other` (a `tag` field AND a `note` field). The importer aliases
// `Payload as Other` (`import hew::aliassrc::{ Payload as Other }`). The alias
// binding `Other` must denote the SOURCE `aliassrc.Payload`, never the
// same-named export `aliassrc.Other`.
//
// The construction `Other { code: … }` proves the binding: it initialises the
// SOURCE `Payload`'s sole `code` field. Were the alias conflated with the
// export `aliassrc.Other`, the checker would demand the `tag`/`note` fields and
// reject `code`; and were HIR to key the StructInit off the bare binding
// `Other` (rather than the checker-resolved source identity `aliassrc.Payload`)
// the MIR field-order lookup would miss the registered `Payload` layout and
// fall through the field-order fail-closed. Reading `code` back confirms the
// SOURCE layout was constructed.
//
// Harness verb: hew run
// Expected: the aliased construction builds `Payload` and reads `code` as 11.
import hew::aliassrc::{ Payload as Other };

fn main() {
    let v = Other { code: 11 };
    println(f"code={v.code}");
}
